Otherwise, a fine Tuesday effort with a couple of layers of theming.  Blasts from the past of tv with Partridge Family and Designing Women.  The inclusion of the multi-talented DAVIDBOWIE made me fondly think of his many musical breakthroughs and his acting prowess.

@Xword Junkie

I think "ticks off" and "angers" are on a continuum, but I don't see the former as being as serious as the latter.  YMMV.

I wasn't correcting you; I was providing context.  And although the @name was yours, lots of newbies read the comments, too.

@Dakota

DREW BARRYMORE is on TV daily right now.  And isn't "E.T." a classic movie?

I might sympathize more with you about the other two, but the olds feel the same when there are rappers and current reality stars in the puzzle.

@Dakota

I'm 42, I've never seen anything with Delta Burke or Danny Bonaduce but I have heard the names before and as I got half the crossword clues I found it obvious it was forming their names.

And anyway, I'm sure you'd do better than me on a puzzle themed on current pop stars, do you only consider a puzzle fair if it focuses on your own areas of expertise?

@Dakota 
II am 90 and the people you are complaining about were never exactly household names for me, but I know who David Bowie was, who Drew Barrymore is—no idea about Delta Burke and Danny whats-his-name, but all of them were easy to fill from the crosses.   

I never hesitate to do a look-up when I am hopelessly stuck, but it wasn't necessary for me this time.  With a little a little more time spent on the crosses, it wouldn't have been necessary for you either.

@Barry Ancona

Also, remember that this is a puzzle,  it a trivia contest. There are tricks you can use to figure out a name you don’t know. In this case, you should gather from the revealer that the highlighted names have the initials “DB.” There are only so many first names that start with D. Then, when you have a series of letters like “DA—-B———,” you can probably guess that the first name is DANNY.  

Don’t just throw in the towel when you encounter some unknown trivia. Usually a little logic and some guesswork can get you there.

@Katie

Or, if you're like me—I worked during prime time, and never got hooked on TV. I really don't care to watch TV, go to movies, or stream; and I don't care to clutter up my mind with trivia I have no interest in. I go to IMDB and look up the answers if I can't come up with the names with crosses or guesswork.

Today's answers were fairly easy for me, because I had heard of all the actors, and knew more about Bowie, so didn't have to resort to IMDB at all.

@Jerry
Yes a great movie. But interestingly, the book it's [loosely] based on has a completely different focus: on the sapper whose job is to blow up the bridge. We read far more about him than about the men in the POW camp. And in the end, after pages of turmoil, he only lightly damages the bridge and THAT is the central irony.
  I often feel that a movie doesn't live up to a book, but this is definitely an exception.

